  "narrative": {
    "business": "Adobe Inc. develops various computer software products that enable users to create, transfer, and print electronic documents. In fiscal 2024, the company operated in the following primary business segments: Digital Media, Digital Experience, and Publishing and Advertising. Adobe\u2019s leading software products include Illustrator, Photoshop, In Design, and Acrobat. R&D spending accounted for roughly 18.0% of the company\u2019s total revenues in fiscal \u201924. Has about 30,700 employees. Vanguard Group owns approximately 9.0% of stock. Officers & directors own less than 1% (3/24 proxy). Chairman, President, and CEO: Shantanu Narayen. Inc.: DE. Address: 345 Park Avenue, San Jose, CA 95110-2704. Telephone: 408-536-6000. Internet: www.adobe.com.",
    "analyst_name": "Adam Rosner",
    "commentary_date": "2025-01-31",
    "analyst_commentary": "year ended November 29th). For the fourth quarter, the software designer posted revenues of $5.6 billion, fueled by positive contributions across the business. In addition, profits settled at $3.79 per share, reflecting wellcontrolled operating costs. For fiscal 2025, we think the top line will rise about 10%, to $23.5 billion, with profits of $16.00 per share, in line with our prior forecast. Adobe operates in two main business segments. The Digital Media unit (accounts for over 70% of the business) should hold up nicely. Adobe has a sizable lineup of products, aimed at the creation of digital content. This unit also contains the company\u2019s digital document offerings, including the widely-used Acrobat technology. We think there is ample opportunity for expansion in this arena, as more business is conducted across digital platforms. Elsewhere, the smaller Digital Experience segment is making progress. There is ample demand for marketing and analytics solutions, but there is also considerable competition here. Too, it should be noted that Adobe formed this segment through a series of acquisitions, and some investors may worry about the company\u2019s ability to expand the existing business. However, Adobe does not appear to be advancing as rapidly as it had in the past. To its credit, an effort is being made to introduce AI (Artificial Intelligence) tools across the product line. However, these offerings may take a while to have a concrete impact on financial results. Meanwhile, we are not looking for any major acquisitions at this point. In late December of 2023, the proposed $20 billion Figma purchase was derailed, due to regulatory concerns. Meanwhile, Adobe does seem willing to invest in R&D. These shares lost some ground since our November report. This may be due to recent softness in the technology sector, as well as concerns about Adobe\u2019s outlook. Our projections suggest that this stock offers attractive appreciation potential for the next 3 to 5 years. Value-oriented investors should note that this timely issue now trades at a price-to-earnings multiple that seems a bit more reasonable, relative to its historic range.",
    "fact_nature": "opinion"
  },
